<span id="freeTextContainer18183675803876604134">This book is the first in the series that spins off her Blood series. It takes Tony, a relatively minor character from before and turns him into the main. Though you don&apos;t have to read the other series to understand this one, this book does spoil how the other one ends.<br/><br/>The story is light compared to much fiction, especially compared to the series it spun off of, its tone has a feel that you&apos;d recognize if you read a lot of fanfiction. But that doesn&apos;t detract. It has humor and wryness and a sens</span>
  <span id="freeText18183675803876604134" style="display:none">This book is the first in the series that spins off her Blood series. It takes Tony, a relatively minor character from before and turns him into the main. Though you don't have to read the other series to understand this one, this book does spoil how the other one ends.<br /><br />The story is light compared to much fiction, especially compared to the series it spun off of, its tone has a feel that you'd recognize if you read a lot of fanfiction. But that doesn't detract. It has humor and wryness and a sense of Huff's own fangirl nature seeps through in the varying in jokes about the Vancouver production scene.<br /><br />The plot alone isn't original, but the take on it, her spin is. It kept me intrigued through Tony's journey even if it wasn't EXACTLY new. <br /><br />As a side note, Tony is a well rounded, gay character and you don't see many of those around. Or maybe I just haven't read enough.</span>
